notes.body:
A graph is just nodes + edges. Ninety percent of the work is always the same two steps: (1) build the adjacency list, (2) run BFS or DFS with a `visited` mark so you never process a node twice. Everything else in this module is a variation on that.

**Adjacency list** — your default representation. For nodes numbered `0..n-1`:

```cpp
int n;                              // number of nodes
vector<vector<int>> adj(n);        // adj[u] = list of neighbors of u
for (auto& e : edges) {            // e = {u, v}
    adj[e[0]].push_back(e[1]);
    adj[e[1]].push_back(e[0]);     // OMIT this line if the graph is DIRECTED
}
```

**DFS (recursive)** — dive as deep as possible before backing up. You already have this reflex from trees and backtracking; the only new ingredient is `visited`, because graphs, unlike trees, have cycles.

```cpp
vector<int> visited(n, 0);
function<void(int)> dfs = [&](int u) {
    visited[u] = 1;
    for (int v : adj[u])
        if (!visited[v]) dfs(v);
};
for (int i = 0; i < n; i++)         // handles disconnected graphs
    if (!visited[i]) dfs(i);        // each fresh start = one component
```

That outer loop is not decoration: each time it finds an unvisited node and launches a fresh DFS, you have discovered **one new connected component**. Counting components is literally counting those launches.

**BFS** — explore in expanding rings. Everything at distance 1 first, then distance 2, and so on. This is why BFS gives shortest paths on unweighted graphs: the first time you reach a node, you got there by a minimum-length route.

[[fig:m10-bfs-levels]]

```cpp
vector<int> dist(n, -1);            // -1 = unvisited; also serves as distance
queue<int> q;
q.push(src); dist[src] = 0;
while (!q.empty()) {
    int u = q.front(); q.pop();
    for (int v : adj[u]) {
        if (dist[v] == -1) {        // first time we reach v = shortest dist
            dist[v] = dist[u] + 1;
            q.push(v);
        }
    }
}
```

> [!INTUITION] Why "first reach = shortest"
> The queue always holds nodes in non-decreasing distance order. So when `v` is discovered from `u`, no shorter route to `v` can appear later — anything discovered later sits at the same or a greater level. Setting `dist[v]` once, at first contact, is safe.

> [!PITFALL] Mark visited at PUSH time, not pop time
> The template sets `dist[v]` (the visited mark) the moment `v` is pushed. If you instead mark on pop, the same node can be enqueued many times through different neighbors before it is ever popped — the queue explodes and you TLE. This is the number-one BFS bug.

Most OA graph problems don't even give you edges — they give you a grid. Every cell is a node; its edges go to the 4 (sometimes 8) adjacent cells. You never build an adjacency list; you *compute* neighbors on the fly with the direction-array idiom. Memorize it — you will type it dozens of times:

```cpp
int R = grid.size(), C = grid[0].size();
int dr[] = {-1, 1, 0, 0}, dc[] = {0, 0, -1, 1};   // up, down, left, right
// inside your loop, for cell (r, c):
for (int k = 0; k < 4; k++) {
    int nr = r + dr[k], nc = c + dc[k];
    if (nr < 0 || nr >= R || nc < 0 || nc >= C) continue;  // bounds first!
    // ... process (nr, nc)
}
```

[[fig:m10-grid-dirs]]

> [!PITFALL] Bounds before indexing
> The range check on `nr, nc` must come **before** you ever touch `grid[nr][nc]`. Reverse those two and you have an out-of-bounds read — a crash on the judge that is miserable to debug under time pressure.

**Multi-source BFS** — the one genuinely new idea in this section. When many starting points spread *simultaneously* (every rotten orange rots its neighbors, every gate measures distance), do NOT run one BFS per source. Push **all** sources into the queue at level 0, then run one ordinary BFS:

```cpp
queue<pair<int,int>> q;
for (all source cells) { q.push({r,c}); dist[r][c] = 0; }
// then the normal BFS loop — this computes nearest-source distance for every cell
```

The level at which a cell is first reached equals its distance to the **nearest** source — all the waves race outward in parallel and whichever arrives first wins.

[[fig:m10-multi-source]]

> [!ANALOGY]
> Drop several pebbles into a pond at the same instant. Ripples expand together, and each point of the pond is first disturbed by the ripple from its *closest* pebble. Multi-source BFS is exactly that — one queue, several pebbles.

> [!EXAM]
> "Distance to the nearest X for every cell" (01 Matrix, Walls and Gates) is always multi-source BFS *from the X cells*, never per-cell searches. The per-cell version is $O((RC)^2)$ and will TLE by design.

Whenever tasks have "must come before" constraints — courses with prerequisites, build steps, recipe stages — draw a directed edge `b → a` meaning "b unlocks a". A valid ordering of all tasks exists **iff the directed graph has no cycle**; the ordering itself is a *topological sort*.

**Kahn's algorithm (BFS on indegrees)** is the version to reach for first, because it detects cycles as a free side effect. The idea: a node with **indegree 0** has no unmet prerequisites, so it can go first. Remove it, decrement its neighbors' indegrees, and repeat.

[[fig:m10-kahn-peel]]

```cpp
vector<int> indeg(n, 0);
for (int u = 0; u < n; u++)
    for (int v : adj[u]) indeg[v]++;       // directed edge u -> v
queue<int> q;
for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) if (indeg[i] == 0) q.push(i);
vector<int> order;
while (!q.empty()) {
    int u = q.front(); q.pop();
    order.push_back(u);
    for (int v : adj[u])
        if (--indeg[v] == 0) q.push(v);
}
if (order.size() != n) { /* CYCLE — no valid ordering */ }
```

> [!KEY]
> `order.size() != n` at the end means some nodes never dropped to indegree 0 — they are stuck waiting on each other in a **cycle**. Course Schedule I is literally this one check; Course Schedule II just returns `order`.

**DFS variant (post-order + reverse).** Push each node *after* all its descendants are done, then reverse. Same result, handy when you're already writing a DFS:

```cpp
vector<int> visited(n, 0), order;
function<void(int)> dfs = [&](int u) {
    visited[u] = 1;
    for (int v : adj[u]) if (!visited[v]) dfs(v);
    order.push_back(u);                     // push AFTER children = post-order
};
for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) if (!visited[i]) dfs(i);
reverse(order.begin(), order.end());        // reverse post-order = topo order
```

> [!PITFALL] A boolean `visited` cannot detect a DIRECTED cycle
> In a DAG it is completely normal to *revisit* a finished node via a different route (a cross edge) — that is not a cycle. Directed cycle detection by DFS needs **three states**: 0 = unvisited, 1 = in the current recursion stack, 2 = done. Only meeting a state-1 node means a back-edge, i.e. a real cycle. Or just use Kahn and count. This distinction is a classic interview gotcha.

DFS answers "what are the components?" for a *fixed* graph. But some problems feed you edges one at a time and keep asking "are these two connected *yet*?" or "how many groups *now*?". Re-running DFS after every edge is hopeless. **Union-Find (a.k.a. Disjoint Set Union, DSU)** maintains the components incrementally with near-constant-time operations.

The structure: every node points toward a parent; following parents leads to the **root**, which names the whole set. `find(x)` walks to the root; `unite(a, b)` hangs one root under the other. Two optimizations make it fly: **path compression** (every `find` flattens the walked path to point straight at the root) and **union by rank** (always hang the shorter tree under the taller). Together they make each operation effectively $O(\alpha(n))$ — inverse Ackermann, a constant below 5 for any input that fits in the universe.

```cpp
struct DSU {
    vector<int> parent, rank_;
    int components;
    DSU(int n) : parent(n), rank_(n, 0), components(n) {
        iota(parent.begin(), parent.end(), 0);   // each node is its own root
    }
    int find(int x) {                             // path compression
        if (parent[x] != x) parent[x] = find(parent[x]);
        return parent[x];
    }
    bool unite(int a, int b) {                    // returns false if already joined
        a = find(a); b = find(b);
        if (a == b) return false;                 // <-- detects a cycle / redundant edge
        if (rank_[a] < rank_[b]) swap(a, b);
        parent[b] = a;
        if (rank_[a] == rank_[b]) rank_[a]++;
        components--;
        return true;
    }
};
```

[[fig:m10-dsu-merge]]

> [!INTUITION] The return value of `unite` is a cycle detector
> If `find(a) == find(b)`, then `a` and `b` were *already* connected by some path — so adding edge `(a,b)` closes a **cycle**. `unite` returning `false` is exactly that signal, and it is the entire solution to Redundant Connection and Graph Valid Tree.

> [!WARNING]
> DSU *without* path compression + union by rank degrades to $O(n)$ per operation and can TLE on a 10⁵-edge OA input. Copy the struct above verbatim — both optimizations, every time. The `components` counter (start at `n`, decrement on each successful `unite`) answers "how many groups?" with zero extra work.

deepdives.answer:
**Why the naive approaches fail.** Running a separate BFS from each rotten orange and taking the per-cell minimum is $O(\text{sources} \times \text{cells})$ and painful to combine. Simulating minute-by-minute ("scan the whole grid, rot neighbors, repeat") is $O(\text{minutes} \times \text{cells})$ and subtly bug-prone: an orange rotted *this* minute must not rot others in the *same* minute.

> [!INTUITION] All sources, one queue
> Seed the BFS queue with **every** rotten orange at once, at level 0, then run one ordinary BFS. Because BFS expands strictly level by level, the level at which a fresh orange is reached is exactly the minute it rots — measured from its **nearest** rotten source, with all sources racing outward in parallel.

[[fig:m10-multi-source]]

The answer is simply the last level at which anything got rotted.

```cpp
int orangesRotting(vector<vector<int>>& g) {
    int R = g.size(), C = g[0].size(), fresh = 0, minutes = 0;
    queue<pair<int,int>> q;
    for (int r = 0; r < R; r++)
        for (int c = 0; c < C; c++) {
            if (g[r][c] == 2) q.push({r, c});   // ALL sources at level 0
            else if (g[r][c] == 1) fresh++;
        }
    int dr[] = {-1,1,0,0}, dc[] = {0,0,-1,1};
    while (!q.empty() && fresh > 0) {
        int sz = q.size();                       // process one whole level
        for (int i = 0; i < sz; i++) {
            auto [r, c] = q.front(); q.pop();
            for (int k = 0; k < 4; k++) {
                int nr = r+dr[k], nc = c+dc[k];
                if (nr<0||nr>=R||nc<0||nc>=C||g[nr][nc]!=1) continue;
                g[nr][nc] = 2;                    // rot it; mark visited in-place
                fresh--;
                q.push({nr, nc});
            }
        }
        minutes++;                               // one minute per level
    }
    return fresh == 0 ? minutes : -1;            // leftover fresh = unreachable
}
```

**Two details that decide correctness:**

- Advance `minutes` once per **level** — the `sz = q.size()` snapshot fences off exactly one minute's worth of oranges. Incrementing per cell inflates the answer wildly.
- Track `fresh`. It tells you when to stop early (`fresh > 0` in the loop condition avoids counting a phantom extra minute) *and* lets you return -1 for isolated oranges that no wave can reach.

**Complexity:** every cell enters the queue at most once → **time $O(R \cdot C)$, space $O(R \cdot C)$**.

**What generalizes:** any "many things spread simultaneously / distance to nearest X" problem (01 Matrix, Walls and Gates, forest-fire variants) is this exact pattern — seed all sources at level 0, run one BFS.

**Why it's really a graph problem.** Draw a directed edge `b → a` — "b unlocks a". You can finish everything **iff this directed graph has no cycle**: a cycle is a group of courses each waiting on another, forever.

> [!KEY] The Kahn insight
> A course with **indegree 0** has no unmet prerequisites → you can take it right now. Taking it deletes its outgoing edges, which may drop other courses to indegree 0. Keep peeling. If all $n$ courses get taken, the graph was a DAG. If you get stuck with courses remaining but none at indegree 0, the leftovers form a cycle.

[[fig:m10-kahn-peel]]

```cpp
bool canFinish(int n, vector<vector<int>>& pre) {
    vector<vector<int>> adj(n);
    vector<int> indeg(n, 0);
    for (auto& p : pre) { adj[p[1]].push_back(p[0]); indeg[p[0]]++; }  // b -> a
    queue<int> q;
    for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) if (indeg[i] == 0) q.push(i);
    int taken = 0;
    while (!q.empty()) {
        int u = q.front(); q.pop(); taken++;
        for (int v : adj[u]) if (--indeg[v] == 0) q.push(v);
    }
    return taken == n;                            // all taken => no cycle
}
```

**Course Schedule II is free once you have this:** collect the popped nodes into an `order` vector; return it if `taken == n`, else return `{}`. The pop sequence *is* a valid build order.

**Complexity:** each node is pushed/popped once, each edge decremented once → **time $O(V+E)$, space $O(V+E)$**.

> [!PITFALL] The DFS alternative needs 3 colors
> Directed cycle detection by DFS requires three states: 0 = unvisited, 1 = **in the current recursion stack**, 2 = done. Reaching a state-1 node means a back-edge → cycle. A plain boolean `visited` is NOT enough for directed graphs — it flags ordinary DAG cross-edges as "cycles" or misses real ones depending on how you write it. This is a classic interview gotcha; Kahn sidesteps it entirely.

**What generalizes:** any "order tasks under dependencies" question — build systems, compilation order, recipe steps — is Kahn verbatim, with cycle detection included for free.

**Why the naive approach fails.** DFS *from every cell* asking "can I reach the Pacific? the Atlantic?" costs up to a full grid traversal per cell — $O((R \cdot C)^2)$ overall. On a 200×200 grid that's ~1.6 billion steps. Dead on arrival.

> [!INTUITION] Invert the question
> Instead of "which cells can reach the ocean?", ask "which cells can the ocean reach if water flowed **uphill**?" Start from all ocean-border cells and traverse only to neighbors with height **≥** the current cell (the reverse of the real rule). Every cell touched can drain to that ocean. Two traversals — one per ocean — then intersect. Total: $O(R \cdot C)$.

```cpp
void bfsReach(vector<vector<int>>& h, queue<pair<int,int>>& q, vector<vector<bool>>& reach) {
    int R = h.size(), C = h[0].size();
    int dr[] = {-1,1,0,0}, dc[] = {0,0,-1,1};
    while (!q.empty()) {
        auto [r, c] = q.front(); q.pop();
        for (int k = 0; k < 4; k++) {
            int nr = r+dr[k], nc = c+dc[k];
            if (nr<0||nr>=R||nc<0||nc>=C||reach[nr][nc]) continue;
            if (h[nr][nc] < h[r][c]) continue;    // UPHILL only (reversed flow)
            reach[nr][nc] = true;
            q.push({nr, nc});
        }
    }
}
```

**Assembly:** seed one queue with every Pacific-border cell (top row + left column) and a second with every Atlantic-border cell (bottom row + right column). Run `bfsReach` on each with its own `reach` grid, then collect every cell where **both** grids are true.

**Complexity:** each traversal visits each cell at most once → **time $O(R \cdot C)$, space $O(R \cdot C)$**.

**What generalizes:** *swap the direction of the relation and start from the goal.* The same mental unlock powers Surrounded Regions (traverse from the border to find the *un*-captured cells) and many "which states can reach a target" problems — search backward from the target instead of forward from everywhere.
